 Trafficking: Children","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what arrangements are in place to provide ongoing specialist support to young people in any period between leaving the Independent Child Trafficking Advocate scheme at 18 years old and receiving a conclusive grounds decision under the National Referral Mechanism.","false","Biography information for Lord McColl of Dulwich",,"Lord McColl of Dulwich","HL10890"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/993363","Home Office","true","2018-10-31","<p><del class="ministerial">We have provided a comprehensive funding settlement that enables police forces to carry out their important work and meet their financial obligations, including national insurance contributions.</del></p><p><del class="ministerial">In 2018/19 we increased total investment in the police system by over £460m. This includes £280m in force funding from increases in Council Tax precept income.</del></p><p><ins class="ministerial">From January 2017 to January 2018, 12 children exited the Independent Child Trafficking Advocate (ICTA) service because they turned 18. The data collected by the Home Office is anonymised for evaluation purposes. It is therefore not possible to cross-reference this with decision-making data from the National Referral Mechanism (NRM). More information on the ICTA service and children who exited support can be found in the Interim Report published by the Home Office in July, and the accompanying data tables on <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/an-assessment-of-independent-child-trafficking-advocates-interim-findings" target="_blank">Gov.UK</a>.</ins></p><p><ins class="ministerial"> On turning 18, any young person who is awaiting an NRM decision, becomes eligible for support from The Salvation Army through the Victim Care Contract. This includes outreach and accommodation support where necessary. We are currently preparing to retender this contact which will be operational from 1 April 2020 and will include drop in services for up to 6 months post-conclusive grounds decision. It is part of the ICTA’s role to ensure they effectively transition children turning 18 into appropriate support upon leaving the ICTA service.</ins></p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford",,"2018-10-31T15:02:54.803Z","2018-11-01T12:30:19.887Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/993363/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/993363/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/993363/answer",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/993363/answer/previousversion/82049","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-10-22","Slavery: Children","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government whether the proposed drop-in centres intended to offer support to victims of modern slavery after a positive conclusive grounds decision will be available to young people who entered the National Referral Mechanism as children but have since turned 18 years old.","false","Biography information for Lord McColl of Dulwich",,"Lord McColl of Dulwich","HL10891"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/993364","Department for Transport","false","2018-11-05","<p>Motor insurers are responsible for setting the terms and conditions of the policies that they offer and it is for them to decide the level of risk that they take in issuing any policy to a given applicant.</p><p> </p><p>The Government recognises that the cost of motor insurance can be high for new drivers. Motor insurance premiums can vary according to the potential risk that a driver poses and this can include factors such as the age of the applicant, the types of vehicle being driven, the postal area where the applicant lives and the driving experience of the applicant.</p><p> </p><p>As promised in the Road Safety Statement, the Department for Transport has commissioned a £2 million research programme to explore the effectiveness of a range of measures to improve the safety of young and novice drivers, both before they take their test and after they have passed. The Government would like to see improvements in young driver safety reflected in their insurance premiums.</p>",,"Baroness Sugg",,"2018-11-05T16:39:40.727Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/993364/answer","Biography information for Baroness Sugg","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/993364/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/993364/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2018-10-22","Motor Vehicles: Insurance","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what assessment they have made of the cost of vehicle insurance for young people between the ages of 17 and 20 years old; and the implications of such costs on the employment prospects for young people in deprived areas.","false","Biography information for Lord Mawson",,"Lord Mawson","HL10892"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/993365","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-11-05","<p>NHS England has advised that it is not possible to provide a comprehensive list of drugs that are available specifically for blood cancer or how much the National Health Service spends on blood cancer drugs as cancer drugs are often licenced for multiple different types of cancer.</p>",,"Lord O'Shaughnessy",,"2018-11-05T14:29:39.827Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/993365/answer","Biography information for Lord O'Shaughnessy","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/993365/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/993365/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-10-22","Haematological Cancer: Drugs","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government (1) how many drugs were available on the NHS for the treatment of blood cancer, and (2) how much the NHS spent on blood cancer drugs, in each of the past five years.","false","Biography information for Lord Mendelsohn",,"Lord Mendelsohn","HL10893"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/993366","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-11-05","<p>NHS England is unable to provide current or previous spend on drugs specifically for blood cancer as many of these drugs have multiple indications. For the same reason it is not possible to estimate future spend.</p>",,"Lord O'Shaughnessy",,"2018-11-05T13:36:52.667Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/993366/answer","Biography information for Lord O'Shaughnessy","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/993366/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/993366/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-10-22","Haematological Cancer: Drugs","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what is the current level of spending by the NHS on blood cancer treatment; and what estimate they have made of the proportion of the NHS budget that will be spent on blood cancer treatments in each of the next five years.","false","Biography information for Lord Mendelsohn",,"Lord Mendelsohn","HL10894"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/993367","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-11-05","<p>The National Institute for Health and Care Excellence (NICE) is an independent body and is responsible for determining the processes it uses in the development of its guidance.</p><p>NICE has advised that it has no plans to consult on changes to its processes as it has been able to use its existing structures to ensure NHS England’s intended commissioning criteria are included within the appraisal process. NICE’s existing technology appraisal process that was updated in April 2018 already allows input from NHS England at various points.</p><p>Patient groups that are registered stakeholders participating in each technology appraisal will be able to provide their views on NHS England’s proposed commissioning criteria as part of the technical engagement step. Where applicable, all patient groups and individual patients have the opportunity to comment during consultation on an appraisal consultation document.</p>",,"Lord O'Shaughnessy","HL10896","2018-11-05T15:13:35.9Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/993367/answer","Biography information for Lord O'Shaughnessy","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/993367/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/993367/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-10-22","Medical Treatments","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what plans they have to consult on proposals to incorporate input from NHS England into the NICE technology appraisal process when determining treatment criteria.","false","Biography information for Lord Mendelsohn",,"Lord Mendelsohn","HL10895"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/993368","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-11-05","<p>The National Institute for Health and Care Excellence (NICE) is an independent body and is responsible for determining the processes it uses in the development of its guidance.</p><p>NICE has advised that it has no plans to consult on changes to its processes as it has been able to use its existing structures to ensure NHS England’s intended commissioning criteria are included within the appraisal process. NICE’s existing technology appraisal process that was updated in April 2018 already allows input from NHS England at various points.</p><p>Patient groups that are registered stakeholders participating in each technology appraisal will be able to provide their views on NHS England’s proposed commissioning criteria as part of the technical engagement step. Where applicable, all patient groups and individual patients have the opportunity to comment during consultation on an appraisal consultation document.</p>",,"Lord O'Shaughnessy","HL10895","2018-11-05T15:13:35.947Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/993368/answer","Biography information for Lord O'Shaughnessy","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/993368/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/993368/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-10-22","Medical Treatments","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what plans they have to ensure patient groups contribute to the development of treatment criteria for NICE approved treatments in the future.","false","Biography information for Lord Mendelsohn",,"Lord Mendelsohn","HL10896"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/993369","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2018-10-31","<p>The UK has a strong bilateral partnership with Ethiopia, a key ally in the Horn of Africa. We will continue to invest in growing an equitable relationship, built on shared values, and with the shared aim of creating jobs and increasing prosperity, including by increasing the number of staff at the British Embassy in Addis Ababa.</p><p>Government Ministers regularly meet with their Ethiopian counterparts to discuss cooperation across a range of issues. The Secretary of State for Defence and the Secretary of State for International Development both visited Addis Ababa in August; the latter met with Prime Minister Abiy and discussed, inter-alia, the importance of inclusiveness and establishing accountability as part of his reform agenda. The Minister of State for Africa visited at the beginning of October, participating in constructive Aid Talks, which, while covering the breadth of issues identified in the 2018 Partnership Principles Assessment, focused on the economy. The Minister for Africa also, on 16 October, opened the UK-Ethiopia Trade and Investment Forum here in London, recognising the 80% growth in total trade in goods and services between the UK and Ethiopia in 2017 as a clear signal of our evolving, modern partnership.</p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon",,"2018-10-31T12:08:16.54Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/993369/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/993369/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/993369/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2018-10-22","Ethiopia: Foreign Relations","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what assessment they have made of the present state of Anglo–Ethiopian relations.","false","Biography information for Lord Patten",,"Lord Patten","HL10897"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/993370","Department for International Trade","false","2018-11-05","<p>Ethiopia is one of the fastest growing economies in the world and has sustained strong and consistent growth for 14 years. The trading relationship between the UK and Ethiopia is currently worth £699m per annum.</p><p>In Ethiopia the Government is promoting bilateral trading opportunities in a number of industries, including aerospace, infrastructure and renewable-energy.</p><p>My Rt Hon Friend the Secretary of State for International Trade has recently appointed the first HM Trade Commissioner to Africa, who champions trade between the UK and the continent. In addition, my hon Friend for Stafford (Jeremy Lefroy MP) is the Prime Minister’s Trade Envoy and has visited Ethiopia 5 times to promote UK trade and investment to the country.</p>",,"Baroness Fairhead",,"2018-11-05T17:54:53.037Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/993370/answer","Biography information for Baroness Fairhead","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/993370/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/993370/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2018-10-22","Overseas Trade: Ethiopia","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what assessment they have made of economic and trade relations between the UK and Ethiopia.","false","Biography information for Lord Patten",,"Lord Patten","HL10898"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/993371","Department for International Development","false","2018-11-02","<p>The Manjo people in Southern Ethiopia have faced long standing social, political and economic marginalisation. Consequently, they have not benefitted equally from Ethiopia’s development gains. Neither have they been able to fully exercise their human rights, including that of religious freedom.</p><p> </p><p>DFID made an assessment of the situation of the Manjo through the first phase of the Civil Society Support Programme (2011-16), to which the UK contributed £14m. The programme supported interventions by local civil society organisations to address the underlying factors that maintain social and religious marginalisation. Community dialogue events sought to change cultural attitudes towards the Manjo. The second phase of the programme will continue to have a focus on marginalised communities, including the Manjo, through grants and strategic government engagement.</p>",,"Lord Bates",,"2018-11-02T14:18:00.133Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/993371/answer","Biography information for Lord Bates","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/993371/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/993371/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2018-10-22","Ethiopia: Ethnic Groups","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what assessment they have made of the (1) aid available to, and (2) religious freedoms of, the Manjo peoples living in the Sheka zone of the Southern region of Ethiopia.","false","Biography information for Lord Patten",,"Lord Patten","HL10899"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/993372","Department for Transport","false","2018-11-05","<p><strong> </strong></p><p>The Secretary of State for Transport has appointed the Office for Product Safety and Standards, within the Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, as the Regulator for the Alternative Fuels Infrastructure Regulations 2017. The Regulator is empowered to enforce the Regulations as necessary. Any information regarding a potential breach of the Regulations should be sent to: <a href="https://www.rohs.bis.gov.uk/enquiry/" target="_blank">https://www.rohs.bis.gov.uk/enquiry/</a></p>",,"Baroness Sugg","HL10901","2018-11-05T17:28:23.783Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/993372/answer","Biography information for Baroness Sugg","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/993372/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/993372/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2018-10-22","Electric Vehicles: Charging Points","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what steps they are taking to ensure full enforcement of the Alternative Fuels Access Regulations 2017 provision for ad hoc access to electric vehicle charging points.","false","Biography information for Baroness Randerson",,"Baroness Randerson","HL10900"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/993373","Department for Transport","false","2018-11-05","<p><strong> </strong></p><p>The Secretary of State for Transport has appointed the Office for Product Safety and Standards, within the Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, as the Regulator for the Alternative Fuels Infrastructure Regulations 2017. The Regulator is empowered to enforce the Regulations as necessary. Any information regarding a potential breach of the Regulations should be sent to: <a href="https://www.rohs.bis.gov.uk/enquiry/" target="_blank">https://www.rohs.bis.gov.uk/enquiry/</a></p>",,"Baroness Sugg","HL10900","2018-11-05T17:28:23.833Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/993373/answer","Biography information for Baroness Sugg","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/993373/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/993373/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2018-10-22","Electric Vehicles: Charging Points","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what steps they are taking to ensure that where companies require users to be members of a specific scheme in order to access electric vehicle charging points such requirements are compatible with the Alternative Fuels Access Regulations 2017.","false","Biography information for Baroness Randerson",,"Baroness Randerson","HL10901"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/993374","Department for Transport","false","2018-10-31","<p>The drivers’ hours and working time rules for mobile workers are currently harmonised at EU level and implemented in the UK through domestic legislation. The EU (Withdrawal) Act 2018 retains directly-applicable EU laws, including relating to these rules. The Government is preparing secondary legislation under this Act to ensure that the statute book continues to function after 29 March 2019, for example by correcting procedural deficiencies in retained EU law. There are no plans to amend the substance of these rules, which the Government recognises are an important road safety measure.</p>",,"Baroness Sugg",,"2018-10-31T15:21:45.827Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/993374/answer","Biography information for Baroness Sugg","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/993374/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/993374/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2018-10-22","Driving: Working Hours","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government whether they intend to maintain the standards governing the working hours of professional drivers set out in the Road Transport (Working Time) Regulations 2005 after Brexit.","false","Biography information for Baroness Randerson",,"Baroness Randerson","HL10902"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/993375","Department for Transport","false","2018-10-31","<p>The drivers’ hours and working time rules for mobile workers are currently harmonised at EU level and implemented in the UK through domestic legislation. The EU (Withdrawal) Act 2018 retains directly-applicable EU laws, including relating to these rules. The Government is preparing secondary legislation under this Act to ensure that the statute book continues to function after 29 March 2019, for example by correcting procedural deficiencies in retained EU law. There are no plans to amend the substance of these rules, which the Government recognises are an important road safety measure.</p>",,"Baroness Sugg",,"2018-10-31T15:20:21.65Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/993375/answer","Biography information for Baroness Sugg","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/993375/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/993375/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2018-10-22","Driving: Working Hours","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what plans, if any, they have to reduce the number of permitted driver hours under the Road Transport (Working Time) Regulations 2005 after Brexit.","false","Biography information for Baroness Randerson",,"Baroness Randerson","HL10903"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/993376","Home Office","false","2018-11-13","<p>Home Office policy is not to deport foreign nationals from the UK if to do so would breach the UK’s international obligations under the European Convention on Human Rights.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford",,"2018-11-13T17:53:04.837Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/993376/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/993376/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/993376/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-10-22","Capital Punishment","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government how many individuals have been deported from the UK to countries where people can be sentenced to death without a death penalty assurance being sought since 2001.","false","Biography information for The Lord Bishop of St Albans",,"The Lord Bishop of St Albans","HL10904"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/993377","Department for International Trade","false","2018-11-05","<p>The situation in Saudi Arabia is kept under careful review and decisions are made on a case by case basis.</p><p>Export licence applications are carefully assessed against the Consolidated EU and National Arms Export Licensing Criteria. A licence would not be granted if to do so was inconsistent with the Criteria. The policy remains as announced to parliament in a Written Ministerial Statement on 25 March 2014: https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm201314/cmhansrd/cm140325/wmstext/140325m0001.htm#14032566000018 .</p><p>The key test for the Government for our continued military exports to Saudi Arabia in relation to International Humanitarian Law (IHL) is whether there is a clear risk that those items might be used in the commission of a serious violation of IHL.</p>",,"Baroness Fairhead",,"2018-11-05T17:58:38.297Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/993377/answer","Biography information for Baroness Fairhead","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/993377/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/993377/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2018-10-22","Arms Trade: Saudi Arabia","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government whether they intend to halt the sale of arms to Saudi Arabia following the confirmation of the cause of death of Jamal Khashoggi.","false","Biography information for Lord Scriven",,"Lord Scriven","HL10905"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/993378","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2018-11-05","<p>​We welcome the investigation and recommendation of the Special Investigations Unit and the subsequent decision of the Minister of Justice to refer the cases of Mohamed Ramadan and Husain Moosa back to the Court of Cassation for retrial. Both the recommendation and decision have been made available in the public domain. We will continue to closely monitor these cases.</p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon",,"2018-11-05T15:25:46.797Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/993378/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/993378/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/993378/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2018-10-22","Bahrain: Political Prisoners","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what representations they have made to the relevant oversight bodies in Bahrain to encourage them to disclose updates on their investigations into the torture allegations presented by Mohammed Ramadan and Husain Moosa.","false","Biography information for Lord Scriven",,"Lord Scriven","HL10906"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/993379","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2018-11-05","<p>Officials from the British Embassy regularly attend court hearings of cases of interest to the UK. We will continue to monitor the cases of Mohamed Ramadan and Husain Ali Moosa closely.</p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon",,"2018-11-05T15:40:25.493Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/993379/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/993379/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/993379/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2018-10-22","Bahrain: Political Prisoners","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government whether officials from the British Embassy in Manama will attend the retrial of political prisoners Mohammed Ramadan and Husain Moosa on 22 October.","false","Biography information for Lord Scriven",,"Lord Scriven","HL10907"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/993380","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2018-11-05","<p>​The UK has a continuing dialogue with the Government of Bahrain and all Bahraini human rights oversight bodies. We continue to encourage those with concerns about treatment in detention to report these to the relevant human rights oversight bodies. We urge these bodies to carry out swift and thorough investigations.</p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon",,"2018-11-05T16:08:20.94Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/993380/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/993380/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/993380/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2018-10-22","Maher al-Khabbaz","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what representations they have made to the government of Bahrain about the failure of Bahrain’s Special Investigations Unit to investigate the (1) allegations of torture on, and (2) use of coerced confessions from political prisoner Maher Abbas al-Khabbaz.","false","Biography information for Lord Scriven",,"Lord Scriven","HL10908"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/993381","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2018-11-05","<p>​I am aware of the response provided by the Bahrain Ministry of Interior Ombudsman's Office as part of their investigations into claims submitted by Sayed Alwadaei. I also understand there is further correspondence between the Ombudsman's Office and Mr Alwadaei regarding this investigation. The UK continues to encourage those with concerns about treatment in detention to report these to the relevant human rights oversight bodies. We urge these bodies to carry out swift and thorough investigations, as appears to be the case in this instance.</p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon",,"2018-11-05T16:07:59.54Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/993381/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/993381/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/993381/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2018-10-22","Bahrain: Political Prisoners","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what assessment they have made of the response provided by the Bahrain Ombudsman on 18 October to the complaint submitted by Sayed Ahmed Alwadaei on 27 September about the (1) assault, and (2) restrictive measure imposed on female political prisoners Hajer Mansoor, Medina Ali and Najah Yusuf by Isa Town prison authorities.","false","Biography information for Lord Scriven",,"Lord Scriven","HL10909"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/993382","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2018-11-05","<p>​I am aware of the protests Hajer Mansoor, Medina Ali and Najah Yusuf have initiated in Bahrain. The UK continues to encourage those with concerns about treatment in detention to report these to the relevant human rights oversight bodies. We urge these bodies to carry out swift and thorough investigations.</p><p>I understand that family members of Mrs Mansoor have been in direct contact with the oversight bodies. I am aware that the National Institution for Human Rights have also recently carried out an inspection of Isa Town Detention Facility.</p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon",,"2018-11-05T16:08:58.873Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/993382/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/993382/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/993382/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2018-10-22","Bahrain: Political Prisoners","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what assessment they have made of the hunger strike by female activists Hajer Mansoor, Medina Ali and Najah Yusuf to protest the restrictions on phone calls, family visits and free time outside the cell imposed by the Isa Town Prison administration in Bahrain; and what representations they have made to the government of Bahrain to ensure inmates are treated in line with international standards.","false","Biography information for Lord Scriven",,"Lord Scriven","HL10910"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/993383","Home Office","false","2018-11-05","<p>Following the conclusion of an investigation into the campaign spending of Vote Leave and other campaigners during the 2016 EU referendum, the Electoral Commission made two referrals to the Metropolitan Police Service (MPS) regarding potential criminal offences under the Political Parties, Elections and Referendums Act 2000. The first referral was received by the MPS on 11 May 2018 and the second was received on 17 July 2018. On 7 September 2018 the MPS received over 900 documents from the Electoral Commission in relation to both referrals.</p><p>The decision to launch an investigation is entirely an operational matter for the police. It would not be appropriate for Ministers to comment on operational decisions made by the MPS concerning the Electoral Commission’s referrals.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford","HL10912","2018-11-05T12:29:39.277Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/993383/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/993383/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/993383/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-10-22","UK Membership of EU: Referendums","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what assessment they have made of the time taken between the Metropolitan Police being notified by the Electoral Commission of possible breaches of electoral law by Leave.EU and their collection of relevant evidence from the Electoral Commission.","false","Biography information for Lord Strasburger",,"Lord Strasburger","HL10911"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/993384","Home Office","false","2018-11-05","<p>Following the conclusion of an investigation into the campaign spending of Vote Leave and other campaigners during the 2016 EU referendum, the Electoral Commission made two referrals to the Metropolitan Police Service (MPS) regarding potential criminal offences under the Political Parties, Elections and Referendums Act 2000. The first referral was received by the MPS on 11 May 2018 and the second was received on 17 July 2018. On 7 September 2018 the MPS received over 900 documents from the Electoral Commission in relation to both referrals.</p><p>The decision to launch an investigation is entirely an operational matter for the police. It would not be appropriate for Ministers to comment on operational decisions made by the MPS concerning the Electoral Commission’s referrals.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford","HL10911","2018-11-05T12:29:39.337Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/993384/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/993384/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/993384/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-10-22","UK Membership of EU: Referendums","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what steps they are taking to ensure that any breaking of electoral law by pro-leave campaigns during the referendum is investigated; and in what timeframe they anticipate such investigations taking place.","false","Biography information for Lord Strasburger",,"Lord Strasburger","HL10912"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/993385","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-11-05","<p>The Government has made no such assessment, although the National Health Service already utilises a range of flexibilities to enable patients to access medicines. We will continue to work with stakeholders as to how these flexibilities may be used further or whether we may need more.</p>",,"Lord O'Shaughnessy",,"2018-11-05T16:06:59.493Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/993385/answer","Biography information for Lord O'Shaughnessy","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/993385/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/993385/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-10-22","Pharmacy","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what assessment they have made of the recommendation by The Royal Pharmaceutical Society to give pharmacists powers to switch patients to new medications without consulting their GPs in the event of drugs shortages after Brexit.","false","Biography information for Lord Taylor of Warwick",,"Lord Taylor of Warwick","HL10913"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/993386","Home Office","false","2018-10-31","<p>There is no limit on the number of international students who can come to study in the UK, and no intention to impose one.</p><p>The UK remains the second most popular destination in the world for international higher education students. In the year ending June 2018, the number of University-sponsored study visa applications (main applicants) rose 7%. Visa applications from university students are now 27% higher than they were in 2010.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford","HL10916","2018-10-31T13:02:02.557Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/993386/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/993386/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/993386/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-10-22","Entry Clearances: Overseas Students","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what assessment they have made of the analysis by Universities UK Estimates of lost higher education export revenue, 22 October, of the impact on universities of the restrictions on visas for foreign students.","false","Biography information for Lord Taylor of Warwick",,"Lord Taylor of Warwick","HL10914"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/993387","Home Office","false","2018-10-31","<p>The Migration Advisory Committee (MAC) recently published its review of the impact of International Students in the UK. The MAC made several recommendations regarding port-study work, though they did not recommend a separate post-study work visa.</p><p>We will be carefully considering the recommendations made in the report and will be responding in due course.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford",,"2018-10-31T13:02:14.45Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/993387/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/993387/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/993387/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-10-22","Entry Clearances: Overseas Students","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what assessment they have made of the case for a graduate talent visa to allow international students to gain work experience in the UK for up to two years after graduating.","false","Biography information for Lord Taylor of Warwick",,"Lord Taylor of Warwick","HL10915"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/993388","Home Office","false","2018-10-31","<p>There is no limit on the number of international students who can come to study in the UK, and no intention to impose one.</p><p>The UK remains the second most popular destination in the world for international higher education students. In the year ending June 2018, the number of University-sponsored study visa applications (main applicants) rose 7%. Visa applications from university students are now 27% higher than they were in 2010.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford","HL10914","2018-10-31T13:02:02.623Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/993388/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/993388/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/993388/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-10-22","Entry Clearances: Overseas Students","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what assessment they have made of the analysis by Universities UK Estimates of lost higher education export revenue, 22 October, of the impact on tax revenues as a result of the restrictions on visas for foreign students.","false","Biography information for Lord Taylor of Warwick",,"Lord Taylor of Warwick","HL10916"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/993389","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2018-11-05","<p>​The Government has repeatedly made clear to the Israeli authorities our serious concern at the increase in demolitions of Palestinian properties in Area C of the West Bank and in East Jerusalem. In all but the most exceptional circumstances, demolitions are contrary to International Humanitarian Law. The practice causes unnecessary suffering to ordinary Palestinians and is harmful to the peace process. We call on the Israeli authorities to cease the policy of demolitions and provide a clear, transparent route to construction for Palestinians in Area C.</p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon",,"2018-11-05T15:34:26.307Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/993389/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/993389/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/993389/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2018-10-22","Israel: West Bank","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what action they intend to take regarding the demolition of Palestinian structures in the West Bank by Israeli forces.","false","Biography information for Baroness Tonge",,"Baroness Tonge","HL10917"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/993390","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2018-11-05","<p>​While we have not had any recent discussions with the Israeli authorities on this issue, we condemn all extremist violence, including attacks against religious buildings. Officials from our Embassy in Tel Aviv are in regular contact with representatives of churches on a range of issues, including concerns about attacks on places of worship.</p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon",,"2018-11-05T15:26:03.627Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/993390/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/993390/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/993390/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2018-10-22","Israel: Christianity","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what representations they are making to the government of Israel about vandalism of Christian property in both Israel and the West Bank.","false","Biography information for Baroness Tonge",,"Baroness Tonge","HL10918"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/993391","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2018-11-05","<p>The UK voted in favour of a UN General Assembly resolution that gives the Palestinian observer mission to the UN time-bound additional rights to perform the function of the G77 chair.</p><p>The UK is clear that we want to see the creation of a sovereign, independent, contiguous, and viable Palestinian state - living in peace and security, side by side with Israel.</p><p>The UK will recognise a Palestinian state at a time when it best serves the objective of peace. Bilateral recognition in itself cannot end the occupation. Without a negotiated settlement the occupation and the problems that come with it will continue.</p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon",,"2018-11-05T15:39:15.68Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/993391/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/993391/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/993391/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2018-10-22","Palestinians: Recognition of States","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what assessment they have made of the case for recognising the state of Palestine following the UN General Assembly's agreement to allow the Palestinian Authority to participate in meetings as a legitimate state.","false","Biography information for Baroness Tonge",,"Baroness Tonge","HL10919"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/993392","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2018-11-05","<p>The UK has an important strategic partnership with Saudi Arabia involving defence and security cooperation which has saved lives on the streets of Britain. We also have a trading partnership that supports thousands of jobs.</p><p>The UK is committed to upholding the rule of law and the rules-based international system and we expect our partners to do likewise. We make this point very clearly in public and in private.</p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon",,"2018-11-05T15:19:01.687Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/993392/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/993392/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/993392/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2018-10-22","Saudi Arabia: Foreign Relations","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government, further to the report by Kings College London, Security Cooperation with Saudi Arabia: Is it worth it for the UK?, published in September, what assessment they have made of the case to uphold international rules-based order in relation to Saudi Arabia.","false","Biography information for Baroness Tonge",,"Baroness Tonge","HL10920"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/993393","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government","false","2018-10-29","<p>The findings confirm the Government's assessment that we must deal robustly with anti-Muslim hatred and Islamophobia. The Government takes these hate crimes extremely seriously, and we are determined to tackle them. On 16 October the Home Office and the Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government published a refreshed Hate Crime Action Plan to guide Government’s work against all forms of prejudice and discrimination over the the period 2018 to 2020. This includes a strong focus on tackling anti-Muslim hatred and Islamophobia through the Cross-Government Working Group to Tackle Anti-Muslim Hatred. In addition to this, the Government is providing TellMama, a specialist organisation allowing people to report anti-Muslim abuse, with £2.5million between 2016 and 2020, to boost reporting of Islamophobic and anti-Muslim incidents, and to support victims.</p>",,"Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth",,"2018-10-29T15:07:24.813Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/993393/answer","Biography information for Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/993393/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/993393/answer",,,,,"7","Housing, Communities and Local Government","Housing, Communities and Local Government","2018-10-22","Religious Hatred: Islam","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what assessment they have made of findings in the Statistical Bulletin, Hate Crime, England and Wales, 2017–18, published on 18 October, which shows that  more than half of religiously-motivated attacks in 2017–18 were directed at Muslims.","false","Biography information for Baroness Tonge",,"Baroness Tonge","HL10921"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/993394","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2018-11-05","<p>On 23 August 2018 the Minister for the Middle East and North Africa issued a statement on Israeli settlement construction in the West Bank. The previous Foreign Secretary issued a statement expressing concern about the construction permits issued for 31 settlement units in Hebron, for the first time in 15 years. We will continue to raise our concerns about Israel's plans for further settlements with the Israeli authorities. The Government's position is clear: settlements are illegal under international law, present an obstacle to peace, and threaten the physical viability of a two-state solution.</p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon",,"2018-11-05T15:42:35.167Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/993394/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/993394/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/993394/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2018-10-22","Israeli Settlements: Hebron","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what representations they are making to the government of Israel regarding their plan to approve the construction of further settlement housing units in the West Bank city of Hebron.","false","Biography information for Baroness Tonge",,"Baroness Tonge","HL10922"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/989507","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2018-10-22","<p>We welcome the work that the Social Metrics Commission has done. Measuring poverty is complex, and this report offers further insight into that complexity and the additional measures that can be taken into consideration. From discussions with SMC they acknowledge that further work needs to be done (particularly around data availability and quality). We will carefully consider their recommendations and the detail behind the methodology they have employed when this has been made available.</p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson","180731 ; 180732","2018-10-22T16:41:36.47Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/989507/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/989507/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/989507/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2018-10-19","Poverty","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, with reference to the Social Metrics Commission’s new measure of poverty, if will she undertake an assessment of the effect of all government policies on poverty in the UK.","true","Biography information for Dan Jarvis","Barnsley Central","Dan Jarvis","180733"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/991130","Ministry of Defence","false","2018-10-22","<p>I have regular discussions with the Chancellor.</p><p>This Government is committed to spending at least 2% of GDP on defence and the Ministry of Defence’s budget will rise at least 0.5% above inflation every year of this Parliament, taking it to almost £40 billion by 2021.</p>","South Staffordshire","Gavin Williamson",,"2018-10-22T15:45:44.16Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/991130/answer","Biography information for Gavin Williamson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/991130/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/991130/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2018-10-19","Treasury: Public Expenditure","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what recent discussions he has had with the Chancellor of the Exchequer on the future funding of his Department.","false","Biography information for Sir Henry Bellingham","North West Norfolk","Sir Henry Bellingham","907169"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/991134","Department for Education","false","2018-10-24","<p>The government is committed to supporting children and young people whose parents have serious health issues - to improve their own health and wellbeing, and to protect them from excessive or inappropriate caring responsibilities that can impact on their education.</p><p> </p><p>The Department for Education provides schools with £2.4 billion each year in additional funding through the pupil premium to support disadvantaged pupils; each eligible pupil attracts £1,320 to primary schools and £935 to secondary schools. Eligibility for the pupil premium is based largely on children receiving or having previously received free school meals, where parents with serious health issues or disabilities may receive qualifying income-related benefits: some research with young carers aged 14-16 suggests that around 60% already attracted the pupil premium through their eligibility for free school meals.</p><p> </p><p>We expect schools to make effective use of their pupil premium budgets and do not tell them how to use the pupil premium; schools know their pupils best and will spend the grant according to meet pupil needs, which includes where needs are based on a parent’s health issues or disability. Schools are held to account for their use of the pupil premium through school inspection and information in performance tables. Most schools are required to publish details online about the use and impact of the funding.</p><p> </p><p>Beyond this, a wider programme of cross-government action to support those with caring responsibilities is set out in the ‘Carers Action Plan’, a two-year programme of tailored work to support unpaid carers of all ages: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/carers-action-plan-2018-to-2020" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/carers-action-plan-2018-to-2020</a>. Chapter three sets out the government’s action specifically to support young carers and includes plans to improve: identification of young carers; educational opportunities and outcomes; access to support and services; and transition for young adult carers.</p><p> </p><p>In assessing the situation facing young carers, in January 2017 the Department for Education published the omnibus survey report 'The Lives of Young Carers in England’: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/the-lives-of-young-carers-in-england" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/the-lives-of-young-carers-in-england</a>. This was a significant piece of research carried out by the department in partnership with Loughborough University looking to improve understanding of the numbers and needs of young carers and their families.</p><p> </p>","Stratford-on-Avon","Nadhim Zahawi",,"2018-10-24T11:44:16.693Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/991134/answer","Biography information for Nadhim Zahawi","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/991134/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/991134/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2018-10-19","Carers: Children","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what assessment he has made of the adequacy of support offered to (a) primary and (b) secondary school students whose parents have serious health issues.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","181549"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/991135","Cabinet Office","false","2018-10-24","<p>The Government is committed to attracting and retaining the best talent for the Civil Service, across all regions of the UK.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p>The Places for Growth Programme will move Civil Service roles and public bodies outside of London and the South East of England to cities across the UK in line with the Industrial Strategy and Civil Service Estates Strategy. The Programme is bringing together central government units and other departments to work together to develop a comprehensive, evidence-based workforce and place-based strategy for locations around the UK including Birmingham and the West Midlands.</p><p> </p><p>We are developing career pathways for professions across the Civil Service, which enable civil servants to build a common understanding of skills and experience needed at each level, exposing them to the right opportunities to build a successful career in the Civil Service.</p>","Hertsmere","Oliver Dowden",,"2018-10-24T11:15:38.113Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/991135/answer","Biography information for Oliver Dowden","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/991135/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/991135/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2018-10-19","Civil Servants: Labour Turnover","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what plans he has to improve staff retention in the civil service in (a) Coventry, (b) the West Midlands and (c) the UK; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","181550"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/991136","Ministry of Defence","false","2018-10-29","<p>Where the death of a member of the UK Armed Forces has occurred in Scotland and where the family have requested the deceased body to be conveyed into England or Wales for burial or cremation, the arrangements are managed by the family appointed funeral director. This includes notification to the relevant English or Welsh Coroner.</p><p>Repatriation of a deceased member of the UK Armed Forces from any other country in the world back to the UK is managed by the Ministry of Defence (MOD) Joint Casualty and Compassionate Centre (JCCC) through the MOD's Repatriation contractor. This includes the notification to the relevant Coroner.</p><p>In both circumstances the family of the deceased are always supported by MOD welfare teams.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2018-10-29T16:45:25.98Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/991136/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/991136/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/991136/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2018-10-19","Armed Forces: Coroners","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, with reference to the Answer of 26 October 2016 to Question 49922 on armed forces: coroners, what differences there are with respect to coroner notification between a military organised repatriation and funeral from Scotland and organised repatriation of remains from other countries.","false","Biography information for Martin Docherty-Hughes","West Dunbartonshire","Martin Docherty-Hughes","181585"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/991137","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2018-10-26","<p>The Cavity Insultation Guarantee Agency (CIGA), an independent commercial organisation, has a standardised customer journey and resolution process which is detailed on their website: <a href="https://ciga.co.uk/consumer-concerns" target="_blank">https://ciga.co.uk/consumer-concerns</a>. Should a customer believe that CIGA staff have not followed this process they can raise a concern directly with the Chief Executive Officer or alternatively with CIGA’s Consumer Focus Non-Executive Director.</p><p> </p><p>If a Guarantee has been issued, but CIGA have not responded in a manner that is satisfactory to the consumer, the guarantee allows for any dispute between the householder and CIGA to be referred to arbitration. The Independent Arbitration service for customers is provided by the independent Centre for Effective Dispute Resolution (CEDR). Their role is to provide a formal way to resolve disputes between CIGA or CIGA-registered installers and their customers, when other attempts to resolve a dispute have been unsuccessful.</p><p> </p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2018-10-26T13:52:09.84Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/991137/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/991137/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/991137/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2018-10-19","Cavity Insulation Guarantee Agency: Appeals","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what the process is for an appeal against the findings of a Cavity Insulation Guarantee Agency investigation.","false","Biography information for Nick Thomas-Symonds","Torfaen","Nick Thomas-Symonds","181586"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/991138","Ministry of Defence","false","2018-10-29","<p>We are interpreting this question as individuals providing direct support to the Dreadnought programme and it excludes sub-contractors and individuals working within the wider nuclear enterprise.</p><p>There are currently 43 employees of the United States Government and US General Dynamics Electric Boat company seconded to the Dreadnought programme and there are 20 UK Government employees working on the Dreadnought programme based in the United States. Employees work on a range of programme elements, such as Nuclear Propulsion and the Common Missile Compartment which support both the US and UK programmes.</p>","Pudsey","Stuart Andrew",,"2018-10-29T16:43:23.37Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/991138/answer","Biography information for Stuart Andrew","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/991138/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/991138/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2018-10-19","USA: Trident Submarines","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, how many (a) employees of the United States Government and the US Electric Boat company have been seconded to the Dreadnought programme and (b) UK Government employees working on the Dreadnought programme are currently based in the United States.","false","Biography information for Caroline Lucas","Brighton, Pavilion","Caroline Lucas","181551"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/991139","Cabinet Office","false","2018-10-26","<p>The primary purpose of the Prosperity Fund is to support inclusive economic development. Programmes contribute to a number of the Sustainable Development Goals, including SDG 13, for example through the development of low carbon development technologies and improving energy efficiency. This is set out in more detail in the Prosperity Fund’s forthcoming Annual Report for 2017/18.</p>","Aylesbury","Mr David Lidington",,"2018-10-26T14:38:18.24Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/991139/answer","Biography information for Sir David Lidington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/991139/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/991139/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2018-10-19","Development Aid: Climate Change","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, for what reasons sustainable development goal (SDG) 13 has not been included in the list of SDGs that the Prosperity Fund focuses on.","false","Biography information for Kate Osamor","Edmonton","Kate Osamor","181587"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/991140","Treasury","false","2018-10-29","<p>Moving to regional centres will save around £300 million up to 2025. HMRC’s Locations Programme will deliver annual cash savings of £74 million in 2025/26, rising to around £90 million from 2028.</p>","Central Devon","Mel Stride",,"2018-10-29T10:58:55.443Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/991140/answer","Biography information for Mel Stride","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/991140/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/991140/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2018-10-19","Revenue and Customs: Reorganisation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Chancellor of the Exchequer, with reference to the oral contribution of the Financial Secretary to the Treasury of 7 March 2018, Official report, column 428, what estimate he has made of the cash savings for 2025-26 onwards arising from the HMRC Building our Future Programme.","false","Biography information for Dr Lisa Cameron","East Kilbride, Strathaven and Lesmahagow","Dr Lisa Cameron","181588"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/991141","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-10-29","<p>The Department is not aware of any primary care building projects under the National Health Service Local Improvement Finance Trust programme that have been put on hold in the last year because of concerns about the economic outlook for the United Kingdom.</p>","North East Cambridgeshire","Stephen Barclay",,"2018-10-29T17:14:05.7Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/991141/answer","Biography information for Stephen Barclay","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/991141/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/991141/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-10-19","NHS: Capital Investment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, what information he holds on the number of  local and primary care building projects under the NHS LIFT programme that have been put on hold in the last year because of concerns about the economic outlook for the UK.","false","Biography information for Siobhain McDonagh","Mitcham and Morden","Siobhain McDonagh","181655"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/991142","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2018-10-25","<p>Basing the assessment on HMRC data has enabled the Child Maintenance Service to significantly speed up the set-up of new cases which can be key to securing regular payments. The previous approach of obtaining the information from parents often led to considerable delays and significant arrears building up on cases right from the start.</p><p> </p><p>Child maintenance is reviewed annually using HMRC data to make sure it is in line with a parent’s circumstances. Between those reviews, parents are required to report any changes in their income that are greater than 25 percent – such changes will trigger a reassessment of the maintenance due.</p><p> </p><p>Income information is provided by HMRC under a data sharing agreement for the most recent complete tax year they hold within the last six years. HMRC determines a tax year as complete when they have accounted for all Pay As You Earn (PAYE) and Self Assessment records.</p><p> </p><p>Each year HMRC receive and process income figures from 33 million Pay As You Earn (PAYE) and 3.3 million Self-Assessment customers. HMRC undertakes compliance activity to ensure that the data reported to them is accurate.</p><p> </p><p>My Department has recently laid regulations which would allow a notional income to be assessed from certain assets. This will ensure that parents who are able to organise their financial affairs to minimise their taxable income, still have an obligation to pay maintenance for their children at a level which reflects their financial circumstances.</p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson","181325 ; 181590","2018-10-25T16:05:26.78Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/991142/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/991142/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/991142/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2018-10-19","Children: Maintenance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, if he will make an assessment of the potential merits of only using the most recent income data in order to calculate child maintenance payments for a non-resident parent.","false","Biography information for Angela Crawley","Lanark and Hamilton East","Angela Crawley","181589"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/991144","Attorney General","false","2018-10-29","<p>By longstanding constitutional convention, the content of advice given by the Attorney General or by any Law Officers, or the fact that such advice has been given, is not disclosed outside of Government.</p><p> </p>","South Swindon","Robert Buckland",,"2018-10-29T12:09:59.17Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/991144/answer","Biography information for Robert Buckland","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/991144/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/991144/answer",,,,,"88","Attorney General","Attorney General","2018-10-19","Veterans: Prosecutions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Attorney General, what discussions he has had with the Secretary of State for Defence on the protection of British military veterans from prosecution; and if he will he make a statement.","false","Biography information for Leo Docherty","Aldershot","Leo Docherty","181591"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/991145","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2018-10-29","<p>The Foreign and Commonwealth Office continues to press Turkey and Saudi Arabia to carry out thorough investigations until responsibilities are clearly established and there is proper accountability and due process for any crimes committed. The Foreign Secretary spoke to the Saudi Foreign Minister on 20 October and I, and, our Ambassador to Riyadh, have subsequently reiterated this to the Foreign Minister. <br> <br>On 24 October, the Prime Minister spoke to King Salman to reiterate the UK’s grave concerns about the murder of Jamal Khashoggi and strongly urged Saudi Arabia to cooperate with the Turkish investigation and to be transparent about the results.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2018-10-29T16:27:50.633Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/991145/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/991145/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/991145/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2018-10-19","Jamal Khashoggi","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what steps his Department is taking to seek to ensure the Saudi Arabian Government and the Turkish Government conduct a thorough and transparent investigation into the disappearance of Jamal Khashoggi.","true","Biography information for Leo Docherty","Aldershot","Leo Docherty","181592"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/991146","Department for Education","false","2018-10-24","<p>My right hon. Friend, the Chancellor of the Exchequer, recently announced £100 million of initial funding for the National Retraining Scheme (NRS). This funding will allow the roll-out of initial elements of the NRS and test what works to help adults reskill as the economy changes. Further details will be provided shortly.</p>","Guildford","Anne Milton",,"2018-10-24T13:57:15.407Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/991146/answer","Biography information for Anne Milton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/991146/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/991146/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2018-10-19","Training","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how much funding has been allocated to the National Retraining Scheme for each of the next five fiscal years; and how much of that funding has been spent.","false","Biography information for Angela Rayner","Ashton-under-Lyne","Angela Rayner","181593"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/991147","Department for Education","false","2018-10-24","<p>The government has committed £24 million to the CITB Construction Skills Fund. This fund will support and incentivise an employer-led approach to construction skills by funding on-site training hubs across England. Funding is due to begin shortly, with the first hubs being rolled out towards the end of the year. This employer-led approach to construction training will help deliver the local skills that firms need, while also meeting the national need for more skilled construction workers.</p><p>As part of the 2017 Autumn Budget, the West Midlands Combined Authority was granted £5 million to support the recruitment of new construction training entrants to underpin the continued growth of the region’s construction industry. This funding, which is separate to the £24 million committed to the CITB Construction Skills Fund, commenced in July 2018 and it will conclude in 2021.</p><p>Finally, the government has allocated £30 million to develop innovative ways to use education technology and artificial intelligence in education to deliver improved learning outcomes. This funding takes effect from the period 2019 to 2020 onwards and further details will be announced shortly. Evidence from these funds and pilots will inform the development of the National Retraining Scheme.</p>","Guildford","Anne Milton",,"2018-10-24T14:23:23.99Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/991147/answer","Biography information for Anne Milton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/991147/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/991147/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2018-10-19","Training","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how much and what proportion of the funding allocated to the National Retraining Scheme pilots in digital and construction skills has been spent.","false","Biography information for Angela Rayner","Ashton-under-Lyne","Angela Rayner","181594"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/991148","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government","false","2018-10-24","<p>My department is funding up to £9.4 million to Oxfordshire Local Enterprise Partnership for the delivery of the A34 Lodge Hill interchange. The Cities and Local Growth Unit requires updates and proof the scheme is on track in order to provide the agreed funding on a yearly basis between 2017/18 – 2020/21. In March 2018 the unit was satisfied the project was on track to be completed as planned and provided the second wave of funding.</p><p>Oxfordshire County Council are the scheme promoter and are leading discussions with Her Majesty’s Government. Highways England are partnering and facilitating discussions with Oxfordshire County Council regularly, and meeting them on a monthly basis as they develop their proposal to add south-facing slips to the A34 Lodge Hill interchange. They are currently compiling the evidence needed to demonstrate that the plans will not have an adverse effect upon the safe and efficient operation of the network.</p>","Rossendale and Darwen","Jake Berry",,"2018-10-24T11:43:09.463Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/991148/answer","Biography information for Jake Berry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/991148/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/991148/answer",,,,,"7","Housing, Communities and Local Government","Housing, Communities and Local Government","2018-10-19","A34: Oxfordshire","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Housing, Communities and Local Government, pursuant to the Answer of 18 October 2018 to Question 179305 on A34: Oxfordshire, what recent discussions his Department's Cities and Local Growth Unit has had with Oxfordshire County Council on the delivery of the A34 Lodge Hill scheme within the planned timescales; what recent assessment that unit has made of whether that scheme will be delivered on time; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Layla Moran","Oxford West and Abingdon","Layla Moran","181595"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/991149","Department for Education","false","2018-10-24","<p>Funding will commence shortly for the Construction Skills fund. The Construction Industry Training Board (CITB) is delivering the Fund on behalf of the Department. CITB have committed to delivering at least 20 training hubs with at least 13,000 learners by March 2020. Funding for the West Midland Combined Authority construction pilot commenced in July 2018 and they have committed to training at least 2,280 new recruits over three years.</p><p>The government has committed up to £30 million to develop innovative ways to use education technology and artificial intelligence in education to deliver improved learning outcomes. This funding takes effect from 2019-20 onwards and further details will be announced shortly.</p>","Guildford","Anne Milton",,"2018-10-24T10:24:59.977Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/991149/answer","Biography information for Anne Milton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/991149/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/991149/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2018-10-19","Training","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how many people have benefited from the construction and digital skills pilots of the National Retraining Scheme.","false","Biography information for Angela Rayner","Ashton-under-Lyne","Angela Rayner","181596"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/991150","Treasury","false","2018-10-24","<p>The Regulation of consumer credit is a matter for the Financial Conduct Authority (FCA). The government has given the FCA strong powers to protect consumers and to take action against firms and individuals that do not meet its standards. In 2017, the FCA issued total fines of £229 million.</p><p> </p><p>FCA rules are based on the principle that money should only be lent to a consumer if they can afford to repay it. The rules set out what is expected of firms, and the sanctions if they lend irresponsibly</p><p> </p><p>Treasury ministers and officials meet regularly with the FCA, and the government will continue to work closely with the FCA to ensure all customers are treated fairly.</p>","Salisbury","John Glen",,"2018-10-24T16:09:00.507Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/991150/answer","Biography information for John Glen","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/991150/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/991150/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2018-10-19","Credit: Interest Rates","1","House of Commons","To ask the Chancellor of the Exchequer, when his Department most recently made representations to the Financial Conduct Authority on enforcing rules on affordability checks for payday loans; and when his Department next plans to make such representations.","false","Biography information for Layla Moran","Oxford West and Abingdon","Layla Moran","181597"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/991151","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2018-10-29","<p>The Secretary of State regularly visits DWP sites, including Jobcentres, in different parts of the country</p><p><strong> </strong></p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2018-10-29T15:43:24.213Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/991151/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/991151/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/991151/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2018-10-19","Department for Work and Pensions: Domestic Visits","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, which Departmental offices and job centres she has visited since her appointment; and if she will make a statement.","true","Biography information for Chris Stephens","Glasgow South West","Chris Stephens","181598"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/991152","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2018-10-24","<p>Employees claiming Universal Credit have no obligation to inform DWP they are receiving benefits.</p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2018-10-24T16:05:37.333Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/991152/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/991152/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/991152/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2018-10-19","Department for Work and Pensions: Universal Credit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what estimate she has made of the (a) number and (b) proportion of staff in receipt of universal credit; and if she will make a statement.","true","Biography information for Chris Stephens","Glasgow South West","Chris Stephens","181599"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/991153","Scotland Office","false","2018-10-25","<p>The Office of the Secretary of Scotland does not hold information on the number or proportion of staff in receipt of universal credit. All staff that join do so on an assignment, loan or secondment from other government bodies, principally the Ministry of Justice and the Scottish Government, who remain the employers.</p>","Dumfriesshire, Clydesdale and Tweeddale","David Mundell",,"2018-10-25T11:31:26.497Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/991153/answer","Biography information for David Mundell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/991153/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/991153/answer",,,,,"2","Scotland","Scotland","2018-10-19","Scotland Office: Universal Credit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Scotland, what estimate he has made of the (a) number and (b) proportion of staff in receipt of universal credit; and if he will make a statement.","true","Biography information for Chris Stephens","Glasgow South West","Chris Stephens","181600"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/991154","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2018-10-26","<p>The Foreign and Commonwealth Office (FCO) has made no assessment of the number or proportion of staff employed by the FCO who may be in receipt of universal credit. This information is not needed by the FCO for employment purposes.​</p>","Rutland and Melton","Sir Alan Duncan",,"2018-10-26T08:28:23.583Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/991154/answer","Biography information for Sir Alan Duncan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/991154/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/991154/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2018-10-19","Foreign and Commonwealth Office: Universal Credit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what estimate he has made of the (a) number and (b) proportion of staff employed by is Department who are in receipt of universal credit; and if he will make a statement.","true","Biography information for Chris Stephens","Glasgow South West","Chris Stephens","181601"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/991155","Department for Exiting the European Union ","false","2018-10-29","<p>The Department for Exiting the European Union does not hold this information. As an employer it is not for the Department to hold information relating to benefits that are claimed or might be claimed by their employees.</p><p> </p>","Fareham","Suella Braverman",,"2018-10-29T17:12:52.297Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/991155/answer","Biography information for Suella Braverman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/991155/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/991155/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union ","Exiting the European Union ","2018-10-19","Department for Exiting the European Union: Universal Credit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, what estimate he has made of the (a) number and (b) proportion of staff employed by his Department in receipt of universal credit; and if he will make a statement.","true","Biography information for Chris Stephens","Glasgow South West","Chris Stephens","181602"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/991156","Home Office","false","2018-11-07","<p>Members of staff apply for universal credit in a personal capacity and there are a number of different factors which determine whether or not an individual is eligible. It is not appropriate for the Department to seek this information from its staff and therefore it is not possible for the Secretary of State for Home Office to make an estimate of numbers, or a statement.</p>","Louth and Horncastle","Victoria Atkins",,"2018-11-07T15:35:56.743Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/991156/answer","Biography information for Victoria Atkins","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/991156/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/991156/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-10-19","Home Office: Universal Credit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what estimate he has made of the (a) number and (b) proportion of staff employed by his Department in receipt of universal credit; and if he will make a statement.","true","Biography information for Chris Stephens","Glasgow South West","Chris Stephens","181603"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/991157","Northern Ireland Office","false","2018-10-24","<p>The Northern Ireland Office does not record or collate information on staff in receipt of Universal Credit.</p>","North West Cambridgeshire","Mr Shailesh Vara",,"2018-10-24T09:28:06.05Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/991157/answer","Biography information for Mr Shailesh Vara","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/991157/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/991157/answer",,,,,"21","Northern Ireland","Northern Ireland","2018-10-19","Northern Ireland Office: Universal Credit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Northern Ireland, what estimate she has made of the (a) number and (b) proportion of staff employed by her Department in receipt of universal credit; and if she will make a statement.","true","Biography information for Chris Stephens","Glasgow South West","Chris Stephens","181604"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/991158","Attorney General","false","2018-10-29","<p>Neither the Attorney General’s Office nor the Law Officers Departments collate information on staff in receipt of universal credit.</p>","South Swindon","Robert Buckland",,"2018-10-29T10:54:36.117Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/991158/answer","Biography information for Robert Buckland","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/991158/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/991158/answer",,,,,"88","Attorney General","Attorney General","2018-10-19","Attorney General: Universal Credit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Attorney General, what estimate he has made of the (a) number and (b) proportion of staff employed by his Department in receipt of universal credit; and if he will make a statement.","true","Biography information for Chris Stephens","Glasgow South West","Chris Stephens","181605"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/991159","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government","false","2018-10-24","<p>The department has no central record from which to determine the number and proportion of its staff currently in receipt of universal credit. There are a number of different factors which determine whether or not an individual is eligible to receive universal credit and, as most of this information is not held centrally, we are unable to estimate the number and proportion of staff eligible to receive or likely to have applied for universal credit.</p>","Rossendale and Darwen","Jake Berry",,"2018-10-24T11:43:36.113Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/991159/answer","Biography information for Jake Berry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/991159/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/991159/answer",,,,,"7","Housing, Communities and Local Government","Housing, Communities and Local Government","2018-10-19","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government: Universal Credit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Housing, Communities and Local Government, what estimate he has made of the (a) number and (b) proportion of staff employed by his Department in receipt of universal credit; and if he will make a statement.","true","Biography information for Chris Stephens","Glasgow South West","Chris Stephens","181606"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/991160","Treasury","false","2018-10-24","<p>HM Treasury does not record or collate information on staff in receipt of universal credit.</p>","Newark","Robert Jenrick",,"2018-10-24T15:56:12.8Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/991160/answer","Biography information for Robert Jenrick","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/991160/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/991160/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2018-10-19","Treasury: Universal Credit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Chancellor of the Exchequer, what estimate he has made of the (a) number and (b) proportion of staff employed by his Department in receipt of universal credit; and if he will make a statement.","true","Biography information for Chris Stephens","Glasgow South West","Chris Stephens","181607"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/991161","Department for Education","false","2018-10-29","<p>The department and its executive agencies do not hold the relevant information to be able to estimate the number and proportion of its staff in receipt of universal credit. Universal credit is dependent on an individual’s circumstances. This includes their housing arrangement, caring responsibilities and dependent children. This information is not held by the department.</p>","Guildford","Anne Milton",,"2018-10-29T16:30:05.067Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/991161/answer","Biography information for Anne Milton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/991161/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/991161/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2018-10-19","Department for Education: Universal Credit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what estimate he has made of the (a) number and (b) proportion of staff employed by his Department in receipt of universal credit; and if he will make a statement.","true","Biography information for Chris Stephens","Glasgow South West","Chris Stephens","181608"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/991162","Ministry of Justice","false","2018-10-29","<p>Members of staff apply for universal credit in a personal capacity and there are a number of different factors which determine whether or not an individual is eligible. The Department has no central record from which to determine the number and proportion of its staff in receipt of universal credit therefore it is not be possible for the Secretary of State for Justice to make an estimate of numbers, or a statement.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Charnwood","Edward Argar",,"2018-10-29T15:10:57.76Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/991162/answer","Biography information for Edward Argar","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/991162/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/991162/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2018-10-19","Ministry of Justice: Universal Credit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what estimate he has made of the (a) number and (b) proportion of staff employed by his Department in receipt of universal credit; and if he will make a statement.","true","Biography information for Chris Stephens","Glasgow South West","Chris Stephens","181609"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/991163","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-10-29","<p>Due to the need to reduce the size of the organisation and change the skills and capability of its workforce, NHS Digital’s restructuring is planned to be delivered in a series of ‘waves’ and is due to be completed by 2020/21. Wave one is currently in progress.</p><p> </p><p>At this stage, NHS Digital estimates that a net overall reduction in headcount of circa 500 full time equivalents is expected. A programme of staff engagement and discussions with staff representatives is in place.</p><p> </p><p>All staff will be affected by the restructuring and will be required to apply for posts in the new organisation structure. Staff are currently located in NHS Digital’s offices in London, Leeds, Southport, Exeter, Southampton, Washington and Redditch.</p><p> </p><p>NHS Digital is working to ensure that it provides every facility to help staff secure suitable alternate employment. A professional outplacement service has been secured to work with displaced staff and NHS Digital is seeking opportunities with other public and private sector employers in the areas affected.</p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock","181553","2018-10-29T17:35:16.183Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/991163/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/991163/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/991163/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-10-19","NHS Digital","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, how many redundancies are planned as a result of the restructure of NHS Digital; and where those staff affected by the Org2 redesign are located.","false","Biography information for Hilary Benn","Leeds Central","Hilary Benn","181552"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/991164","Cabinet Office","false","2018-10-24","<p>Cabinet Office does not record or collate information on staff in receipt of universal credit.</p>","Hertsmere","Oliver Dowden",,"2018-10-24T11:16:29.433Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/991164/answer","Biography information for Oliver Dowden","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/991164/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/991164/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2018-10-19","Cabinet Office: Universal Credit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what estimate he has made of the (a) number and (b) proportion of staff employed by his Department in receipt of universal credit; and if he will make a statement.","true","Biography information for Chris Stephens","Glasgow South West","Chris Stephens","181610"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/991165","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-10-29","<p>Due to the need to reduce the size of the organisation and change the skills and capability of its workforce, NHS Digital’s restructuring is planned to be delivered in a series of ‘waves’ and is due to be completed by 2020/21. Wave one is currently in progress.</p><p> </p><p>At this stage, NHS Digital estimates that a net overall reduction in headcount of circa 500 full time equivalents is expected. A programme of staff engagement and discussions with staff representatives is in place.</p><p> </p><p>All staff will be affected by the restructuring and will be required to apply for posts in the new organisation structure. Staff are currently located in NHS Digital’s offices in London, Leeds, Southport, Exeter, Southampton, Washington and Redditch.</p><p> </p><p>NHS Digital is working to ensure that it provides every facility to help staff secure suitable alternate employment. A professional outplacement service has been secured to work with displaced staff and NHS Digital is seeking opportunities with other public and private sector employers in the areas affected.</p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock","181552","2018-10-29T17:35:16.23Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/991165/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/991165/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/991165/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-10-19","NHS Digital","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, what discussions he has had with NHS Digital staff and their representatives regarding the proposed organisational redesign; and how many staff will be required to reapply for their jobs as a result of the Org2 redesign.","false","Biography information for Hilary Benn","Leeds Central","Hilary Benn","181553"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/991166","Department for International Trade","false","2018-10-29","<p>The Department of International Trade (DIT) does not record or collate information on staff in receipt of Universal Credit.</p><p> </p>","Meon Valley","George Hollingbery",,"2018-10-29T11:58:01.737Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/991166/answer","Biography information for Sir George Hollingbery","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/991166/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/991166/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2018-10-19","Department for International Trade: Universal Credit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, what estimate he has made of the (a) number and (b) proportion of staff employed by his Department in receipt of universal credit; and if he will make a statement.","true","Biography information for Chris Stephens","Glasgow South West","Chris Stephens","181611"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/991167","Women and Equalities","false","2018-10-25","<p>The Government Equalities Office (GEO) do not hold the relevant information to be able to estimate the number and proportion of its staff in receipt of universal credit. Universal credit is dependent on an individual’s circumstances, including their housing arrangement, caring responsibilities and dependent children. This information is not held by GEO.</p>","Louth and Horncastle","Victoria Atkins",,"2018-10-25T09:56:55.977Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/991167/answer","Biography information for Victoria Atkins","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/991167/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/991167/answer",,,,,"31","Women and Equalities","Women and Equalities","2018-10-19","Government Equalities Office: Universal Credit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for Women and Equalities, what estimate he has made of the (a) number and (b) proportion of staff employed by his Department in receipt of universal credit; and if he will make a statement.","true","Biography information for Chris Stephens","Glasgow South West","Chris Stephens","181612"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/991168","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-10-29","<p>Through its training programme, NHS Digital staff are able to request access to training in cyber security, data science and machine learning as appropriate. In addition, there are mandatory requirements for all staff to complete data security training which includes basic cyber security awareness.</p><p> </p><p>Staff have access to more than 6,000 online courses, which are primarily technical in nature, to supplement provision via Civil Service Learning and other providers of classroom-based teaching.</p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock",,"2018-10-29T17:34:13.32Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/991168/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/991168/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/991168/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-10-19","NHS Digital","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, what training has been offered to existing NHS Digital staff on cyber security, data science and machine learning.","false","Biography information for Hilary Benn","Leeds Central","Hilary Benn","181554"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/991169","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-10-29","<p>NHS Digital’s budget for the next three years is shown in the following table:</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong><em> </em></strong></p></td><td><p>2018/19 £ million</p></td><td><p>2019/20 £ million</p></td><td><p>2020/21 £ million</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Revenue</p></td><td><p>354</p></td><td><p>349</p></td><td><p>284</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Capital</p></td><td><p>107</p></td><td><p>92</p></td><td><p>56</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>These budgets have been approved by the Digital Delivery Board as part of the digital transformation portfolio of national programmes and live services that support our vision for using the best digital technology to support the health and social care system. Figures may change in-year or for future years to reflect delivery priorities across the portfolio, subject to agreement by the Digital Delivery Board.</p><p><strong><em> </em></strong></p><p>Funding for 2021/22 will be confirmed through the NHS Long Term Plan and the next Spending Review.</p><p><strong><em> </em></strong></p><p>The figures in the table do not include those programmes in the wider digital transformation portfolio that are not funded from NHS Digital’s budget. These include the £412 million for sustainability and transformation partnerships to improve provider digitisation and the £200 million announced for the next round of global digital exemplars. These will help create the flexibility for local organisations to buy the technology and commodity services they need that meet open national standards of interoperability, privacy and security in line with our vision for digital, data and technology in health and care.</p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock",,"2018-10-29T14:08:41.2Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/991169/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/991169/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/991169/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-10-19","NHS Digital","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, what the budget is for NHS Digital for each year until 2021-22.","false","Biography information for Hilary Benn","Leeds Central","Hilary Benn","181555"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/991170","Department for International Development","false","2018-10-29","<p>DFID does not hold any data on which members of staff are in receipt of universal credit.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2018-10-29T17:41:31.25Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/991170/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/991170/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/991170/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2018-10-19","Department for International Development: Universal Credit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what estimate she has made of the (a) number and (b) proportion of staff employed by her Department in receipt of universal credit; and if she will make a statement.","true","Biography information for Chris Stephens","Glasgow South West","Chris Stephens","181613"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/991171","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2018-10-24","<p>Government is committed to facilitating sustainable financial services that give consumers greater choice in accessing credit. Credit union membership in Great Britain has increased year-on-year since 2014, rising to around 1.32 million members in 2017; this was an increase of over 150,000 individuals over the 3 year period. It is even more encouraging that credit unions are becoming more popular with junior members; in 2017 there were over 139,000 junior members of credit unions in Great Britain compared to around 128,000 in 2014.</p><p> </p><p>The Credit Union Expansion Project (CUEP) aims were for participating credit unions to modernise and grow in a financially sustainable way, over time. The contractor aimed to deliver that by enabling credit unions to access a standardised banking service.</p><p>CUEP has delivered an Automated Loans and Decision tool (ALD) used by over 70 credit unions, centralised services such as a standardised front facing website, and that the ALD has allowed credit unions to achieve up to 40% administrative savings on delivering loans and reduce provision for unpaid debt by over £1 million. CUEP also led to a number of credit unions to merge, and others to work together to develop standardised products and deliver local marketing campaigns to increase membership. CUEP contributed to credit unions on the platform to increase the value of loans made.</p><p>Due to the Contractors failure to meet contractual milestones, DWP terminated the CUEP contract on 16<sup>th</sup> February 2018. Whilst the contractor has not met their contractual agreement, they have delivered a banking platform that allows credit union members to receive a range of banking services and benefit from more affordable credit. At the point the contract was terminated the platform was being used by three credit unions with a total of approximately 16.5k members allowing members to benefit from 24 hour online access to their accounts, and receive faster payments on a loan on the same day, usually within 4 hours.</p>","Hexham","Guy Opperman",,"2018-10-24T15:11:56.777Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/991171/answer","Biography information for Guy Opperman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/991171/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/991171/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2018-10-19","Credit Unions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what assessment she has made of the effectiveness of the credit union expansion project.","false","Biography information for Mr Gregory Campbell","East Londonderry","Mr Gregory Campbell","181556"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/991172","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-10-24","<p>Body Mass Index thresholds for defining underweight, overweight and obesity in children aged 2-18 years have not changed since they were originally introduced in the 1990s.</p>","Winchester","Steve Brine",,"2018-10-24T12:24:56.183Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/991172/answer","Biography information for Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/991172/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/991172/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-10-19","Obesity: Children","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, whether the measurement for assessing whether a child aged between two and 15 years is classified as obese has changed in the last 10 years.","false","Biography information for Mr Gregory Campbell","East Londonderry","Mr Gregory Campbell","181557"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/991173","Treasury","false","2018-10-24","<p>The Government’s shareholding in the Royal Bank of Scotland (RBS) is managed at arm's length and on a commercial basis through UK Government Investments Ltd (UKGI), a company which is wholly owned by the government, with the objective of creating and protecting value for the taxpayer.</p><p> </p><p>In August 2018 RBS announced that it intended to resume the payment of dividends to ordinary shareholders, and that an interim dividend of 2 pence per ordinary share would be paid to shareholders.</p><p> </p><p>On 12 October 2018 the Government received a dividend of just over £150m. All money recovered from our shareholding in RBS will be used to pay down the national debt.</p>","Salisbury","John Glen",,"2018-10-24T16:07:24.317Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/991173/answer","Biography information for John Glen","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/991173/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/991173/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2018-10-19","Royal Bank of Scotland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Chancellor of the Exchequer, how much accrued to the public purse as a result of the Royal Bank of Scotland paying a dividend to shareholders on 12 October 2018.","false","Biography information for Mr Gregory Campbell","East Londonderry","Mr Gregory Campbell","181558"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/991174","Treasury","false","2018-10-24","<p>The government is determined that everyone who is entitled to the National Minimum and Living Wage (NMW) receives it.</p><p> </p><p>There were three successful prosecutions for NMW offences in 2016/17 and one in 2017/18. Breaches of NMW legislation are normally a civil matter, where the consequences for not complying with NMW rules can include fines of 200% of the arrears and public naming.</p><p> </p><p>Criminal prosecution is reserved for the most serious non-compliance, with these cases referred to the Crown Prosecution Service who decide whether to prosecute.</p><p> </p><p>Anyone who feels they have been underpaid NMW should contact the Acas helpline on 0300 123 1100. HM Revenue and Customs (HMRC) review all complaints that are referred to them.</p>","Central Devon","Mel Stride",,"2018-10-24T15:50:16.557Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/991174/answer","Biography information for Mel Stride","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/991174/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/991174/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2018-10-19","Living Wage","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how many employers have been prosecuted for not paying employees the National Living Wage in the last two years.","false","Biography information for Mr Gregory Campbell","East Londonderry","Mr Gregory Campbell","181559"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/991175","Ministry of Justice","false","2018-10-29","<p>In response to PQ 181614, it is only possible to provide figures for anxiety and depression together as they are not held separately and often amalgamated on the central records of sickness absences. The number of band 3-5 prison officers that have taken sick leave due to anxiety or depression in England in each year since 2012 is provided in Table 1 below.</p><p> </p><p>Table 1: Band 3-5 prison officers<sup>1</sup> who took sick leave due to Anxiety or Depression<sup>2 </sup>in England, 2011/12 to 2018/19</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p>Band 3-5 officers that have taken sick leave due to anxiety and depression</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2011/12</p></td><td><p>541</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012/13</p></td><td><p>544</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013/14</p></td><td><p>562</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014/15</p></td><td><p>483</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015/16</p></td><td><p>499</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2016/17<sup>3</sup></p></td><td><p>110</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2017/18<sup>3</sup></p></td><td><p>467</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p> </p><p>In response to PQ 181617, the number of band 3-5 prison officers that have taken sick leave due to stress in England in each year since 2012 is provided in Table 2 below.</p><p> </p><p>Table 2 - Number of Band 3 to 5 prison officers<sup>1 </sup>who took sick leave due to stress<sup>2 </sup>in England, 2011/12 to 2018/19</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p>Band 3-5 officers that have taken sick leave due to stress</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2011/12</p></td><td><p>813</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012/13</p></td><td><p>747</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013/14</p></td><td><p>924</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014/15</p></td><td><p>851</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015/16</p></td><td><p>813</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2016/17<sup>3</sup></p></td><td><p>869</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2017/18<sup>3</sup></p></td><td><p>696</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>Notes to tables 1 and 2</p><p>1 Includes Band 3-4 / Prison Officer (incl. specialists), Band 4 / Supervising Officer and Band 5 / Custodial Managers.</p><p>2 If an individual has taken sick leave more than once due to this reason in the same financial year, they are only counted once.</p><p>3 Between January and March 2017, during migration of data to the Single Operating Platform, an under-recording of sickness absence records occurred. There is therefore likely to be an undercount of working days lost for the 12 months to 31 March 2017 and subsequent under-estimate of average working days lost.</p><p>In response to PQ 181622, information is not available centrally on the number of prison officers that have taken sick leave due to PTSD.</p><p> </p><p>HMPPS is committed to ensuring the health, safety and wellbeing of its staff in England and Wales, with all staff having access to a comprehensive occupational health service and employee assistance programme.</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart","181617 ; 181622","2018-10-29T16:16:57.93Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/991175/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/991175/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/991175/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2018-10-19","Prison Officers: Sick Leave","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what estimate his Department has made of the number of prison officers that have taken sick leave due to (a) anxiety and (b) depression in England in each year since 2012.","false","Biography information for Liz Saville Roberts","Dwyfor Meirionnydd","Liz Saville Roberts","181614"
